    {
      "id": "b99782261f2ac194fe5916f248ebc7cbde07d4cf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 06:06:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nThe problem with the approach in this patch is that if, for some reason, a duplicate or incorrect index is specified for an OST then there would be two OSTs fighting for the single index value.\n\nI don't think it is right to just print a message on the console and ignore this error, since this could lead to serious filesystem corruption (e.g. incorrect MDS orphan recovery deleting many thousands of objects on the wrong OST of the same index, or objects being created on both OSTs and then being unreadable afterward).\n\nA better solution would be to add some kind of \"--force-index\" flag to mkfs.lustre/tunefs.lustre that sends an extra flag to the MGS, and only then will it ignore (possibly with only a small LCONSOLE_INFO(), not an error) the -EADDRINUSE error.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4c3fc9095ce4aa7ab6183b7adaf3ff245ffd7f75",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-09 09:37:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nactually, the target has already been registered in such situation, if we want user to take extra steps to solve the problem, i think we can just add an option for tunefs.lustre to make user be able to clear the virgin flag easily.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
